Good decision. Running without security is fine temporarily, but production must have authentication enabled.

We’ll do this cleanly and safely on your single-node cluster, and keep it extensible for future scaling.

We’ll:
	1.	Enable security in Elasticsearch
	2.	Set passwords for built-in users
	3.	Create an admin user
	4.	Create Kibana user
	5.	Create Filebeat & Metricbeat users

Step by step.

⸻

🔐 STEP 1 — Enable Security in Elasticsearch

Edit:

/etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml

Make sure this is present:

xpack.security.enabled: true

If not there, add it.

Since you are single node:

discovery.type: single-node

Save file.

Restart Elasticsearch:

sudo systemctl restart elasticsearch

It will now start with security enabled.

⸻

🔐 STEP 2 — Set Built-in User Passwords

Now run:

sudo /usr/share/elasticsearch/bin/elasticsearch-reset-password -u elastic

It will generate or allow you to set password.

Do same for kibana_system:

sudo /usr/share/elasticsearch/bin/elasticsearch-reset-password -u kibana_system

Save these passwords securely.

Now test login:

curl -u elastic http://localhost:9200

If it asks for auth → good.

⸻

👑 STEP 3 — Create Admin User (Superuser)

Login using elastic user:

curl -u elastic -X POST "http://localhost:9200/_security/user/admin_user" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '
{
  "password" : "StrongPassword123",
  "roles" : [ "superuser" ],
  "full_name" : "Cluster Admin"
}'

Now test:

curl -u admin_user http://localhost:9200/_cluster/health

This is your primary admin user going forward.

You should avoid using elastic regularly.

⸻

🖥 STEP 4 — Configure Kibana to Use kibana_system

Edit:

/etc/kibana/kibana.yml

Add:

elasticsearch.hosts: ["http://127.0.0.1:9200"]
elasticsearch.username: "kibana_system"
elasticsearch.password: "PASSWORD_YOU_SET"

Restart Kibana:

sudo systemctl restart kibana

Now open:

http://SERVER_IP:5601

Login with:
	•	admin_user
	•	StrongPassword123

⸻

📦 STEP 5 — Create Filebeat User

We follow principle of least privilege.

Create role:

curl -u admin_user -X POST "http://localhost:9200/_security/role/filebeat_writer" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '
{
  "cluster": ["monitor"],
  "indices": [
    {
      "names": [ "filebeat*" ],
      "privileges": ["create_index","create","write","auto_configure"]
    }
  ]
}'

Create user:

curl -u admin_user -X POST "http://localhost:9200/_security/user/filebeat_user" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '
{
  "password" : "FilebeatPass123",
  "roles" : [ "filebeat_writer" ],
  "full_name" : "Filebeat Service User"
}'


⸻

📊 STEP 6 — Create Metricbeat User

Create role:

curl -u admin_user -X POST "http://localhost:9200/_security/role/metricbeat_writer" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '
{
  "cluster": ["monitor"],
  "indices": [
    {
      "names": [ "metricbeat*" ],
      "privileges": ["create_index","create","write","auto_configure"]
    }
  ]
}'

Create user:

curl -u admin_user -X POST "http://localhost:9200/_security/user/metricbeat_user" \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '
{
  "password" : "MetricbeatPass123",
  "roles" : [ "metricbeat_writer" ],
  "full_name" : "Metricbeat Service User"
}'


⸻

🛠 STEP 7 — Update Beats Config

In filebeat.yml:

output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["http://ELASTIC_IP:9200"]
  username: "filebeat_user"
  password: "FilebeatPass123"

In metricbeat.yml:

output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["http://ELASTIC_IP:9200"]
  username: "metricbeat_user"
  password: "MetricbeatPass123"

Restart both services.

⸻

🔎 Verify Everything

Check:

curl -u filebeat_user http://localhost:9200

Check index creation.

Check Kibana login.

Check:

GET _security/user

in Dev Tools.

⸻

⚠ Production Advice

Never:
	•	Use elastic user in production apps
	•	Give superuser to beats
	•	Share admin password

Always:
	•	Create service-specific users
	•	Limit privileges
	•	Rotate passwords quarterly

⸻

🔥 When You Expand to Multi-Node Later

Nothing changes for users.
Security configuration remains valid cluster-wide.

Only discovery settings change.

